Here was the problem: to colonize Mars, you need to send Starship up with s=
upplies, then refuel it and send it back to Earth, all without humans, beca=
use untamed Mars is too risky, and the food to feed them weighs too much.=
=C2=A0
But how do you refuel Starship on a planet with no fuel?=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s actually possible. You can vaporize the ice that=E2=80=99s all=
 over Mars into water, run it through an Electrolyzer to split H2O into Hyd=
rogen and Oxygen, pull CO2 from the atmosphere, then react Hydrogen and CO2=
 using the Sabatier reaction to produce methane. Then compress it, cool it =
to a liquid, fill the tanks, and keep it cool with cryo coolers. The challe=
nge is: that takes a whole lot of power.=C2=A0
Turns out, you would need over three football fields worth of solar panels =
to produce all of that power. Assuming that you could get the panels spread=
 out on Mars=E2=80=99 surface, a task for which the team looked at a number=
 of unorthodox solutions, you=E2=80=99d also need to send up vehicles that =
could anchor them into Mars=E2=80=99 rocky surface. All told, the mass of t=
he panels plus all of the other machines involved in the process would requ=
ire two missions.=C2=A0
Solar was a no-go. But not powering Mars was not an option, either. What to=
