Nuclear on Mars=C2=A0
At first blush, the idea of building nuclear reactors on Mars seems like a =
fantasy, and a potentially wasteful one at that. The age-old knock against =
the space program is that we shouldn=E2=80=99t be spending tens of billions=
 of dollars sending rockets to faraway planets when we have so many issues =
left to solve right here on our own.=C2=A0
The counters to that line of thinking are manifold, ranging from the aspira=
tional to the practical.=C2=A0
On the aspirational side, humans need a frontier, a just-out-of-reach goal =
to strive towards. Plus, making humanity multiplanetary is an insurance pol=
icy on the most valuable thing in the universe.=C2=A0
More practically, the things we develop for space directly improve life on =
earth.=C2=A0
GPS is the most obvious example. Without satellites, your Google Maps would=
n=E2=80=99t work. But the list of products you use in your daily life that =
were born out of or improved by space research is shockingly long: cell pho=
ne cameras, memory foam, scratch-resistant lenses, cordless tools, water fi=
ltration systems, infrared ear thermometers, joysticks, LASIK, artificial l=
imbs, cochlear implants, insulin pumps, soft contact lenses, and baby formu=
la, to name a few. When I finished the London Marathon in April, I was quic=
kly wrapped in a reflective blanket of the sort first developed by NASA in =
1964.=C2=A0
And as Brian Potter highlights in his series on solar [ https://substack.co=
m/redirect/7928f04a-7291-411d-af01-ba4ef2b559cd?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J=
5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], at a time when solar PV electric=
ity was 5x more expensive than batteries and 10,000 more expensive than ele=
ctricity from utilities, satellites =E2=80=9Cwould be the main customer for=
 solar PV for the next 20 years,=E2=80=9D kicking off the technology=E2=80=
=99s earth-altering descent down the cost curve.=C2=A0
That such a disproportionate amount of innovation would come from space res=
earch is counterintuitive but logical.=C2=A0
In Taste for Makers [ https://substack.com/redirect/7089c430-4942-4d35-8514=
-724d89e78979?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Ex=
kRNpU ], Paul Graham wrote that difficulty can lead to good design:
When you have to climb a mountain you toss everything unnecessary out of yo=
ur pack.=C2=A0 And so an architect who has to build on a difficult site, or=
 a small budget, will find that he is forced to produce an elegant design.
Space is harder than a mountain: it is extreme, remote, resource-constraine=
d, and unforgiving. Governments, and private companies, are willing to pay =
large sums of money for solutions, often with indefinite payback periods, i=
n a sort of Pascal=E2=80=99s Wager: that the ultimate gains will be near-in=
finitely large.=C2=A0
Researching for space gives geniuses permission to treat seemingly fantasti=
cal ideas with life-or-death seriousness, with extreme constraints that str=
ip away any considerations except the hard facts, which is exactly what Dou=
g did when he began studying nuclear on Mars.=C2=A0
The first question he asked was: could nuclear achieve SpaceX=E2=80=99s obj=
ectives on Mars?=C2=A0
He started reading papers and playing around in Python, comparing solar ver=
sus nuclear. Pretty soon, he realized that nuclear had a number of advantag=
es.=C2=A0
For one thing, you could fit everything =E2=80=93 the nuclear reactor, the =
Sabatier reactor, and all supporting machines, in one Starship.=C2=A0
Instead of needing to land at the equator, where the sun is, the Starship c=
ould land at Mars=E2=80=99 North Pole, where the ice is.=C2=A0
If you landed right on the ice, you could integrate a reactor right into th=
e rocket, use the heat it produces to melt a hole, let it freeze back up ov=
er the hoses, and end up with a giant well. This is very similar to a proce=
ss that humans have undertaken in the Arctic and Antarctic for decades =E2=
=80=93 a Rodriguez Well, or Rodwell. The first Rodwell, built at Camp Centu=
ry in Greenland, just 800 miles from the North Pole, in 1958, actually drew=
 its power from a nuclear reactor. In October 2020, four years after Doug h=
ad the idea, NASA actually studied the potential of using Rodwells on Mars =
[ https://substack.com/redirect/09b181e8-fd9e-4464-b40d-fea38da4d9a1?j=3Dey=
J1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], and conclud=
ed that it could potentially work, although more studies are needed.=C2=A0
When Doug concluded his study, he had his answer: nuclear could achieve Spa=
ceX=E2=80=99s objectives on Mars. And he had his self-assigned marching ord=
ers: =E2=80=9COK, after we build Starship, this is the thing to do and buil=
d,=E2=80=9D he said, =E2=80=9CThis is the mission statement.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Remember, SpaceX people are dead serious about building a civilization on M=
ars. Elon takes time out of his insane schedule every week for Mars Coloniz=
er. Doug, realizing that humans would have to farm on Mars and that he didn=
=E2=80=99t know how to farm, ripped the grass out of his family=E2=80=99s f=
ront yard and started planting wheat with his kids to practice.=C2=A0
Just getting a rocket to Mars isn=E2=80=99t enough.=C2=A0
To form a society up there, you need power, and more specifically, you need=
 nuclear power.=C2=A0
By that logic, then, figuring out how to build nuclear reactors that you ca=
n put in a Starship and send hurtling [ https://substack.com/redirect/e942a=
d53-1cb6-451f-a8e0-0995b795c68e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjm=
lXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] through more than 100 million miles of space, bec=
ame a problem of civilizational importance, and one that Doug would be will=
ing to spend the rest of his career solving.=C2=A0
He remained at SpaceX for the next three years, getting smarter on nuclear,=
 reading papers and playing with simulations at night while doing his day j=
ob during the day, waiting for the time when he and the team would hit go o=
n their nuclear plans.=C2=A0
Then in January 2019, the Department of Defense=E2=80=99s Strategic Capabil=
ities Office (SCO) announced Project Pele and requested =E2=80=9Cthe develo=
pment of a safe, mobile and advanced nuclear microreactor to support a vari=
ety of Department of Defense missions, such as generating power for remote =
operating bases.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
The DoD had very specific needs: a 1-5 MW high-temperature gas-cooled react=
or (HTGR) mobile nuclear reactor that could be transported in a C17 to be s=
et up quickly in remote locations, that used High-Assay Low-Enriched Uraniu=
m (HALEU) fuel in damage-resistant TRISO (TRIstructural-ISOtropic) fuel par=
ticles, which could be run for several years without refueling and use pass=
ive safety systems that can shut down safely on their own.=C2=A0
Project Pele was a loud, clanging siren for Doug. He knew that the DoD must=
 have put out the request with a supplier in mind =E2=80=93 the Defense Sci=
ence Board reviewed many companies three years prior to creating the progra=
m to ensure its specs were reasonable and that the RFP would generate suffi=
cient replies =E2=80=93 but he thought that SpaceX should compete anyway.=
=C2=A0
Nuclear was too important to the plan, and no new reactors had been built i=
n such a long time. Having the DoD behind the project could change that. It=
 could solve all of nuclear=E2=80=99s challenges =E2=80=93 funding, custome=
r, and regulatory =E2=80=93 within one entity, which meant that the time wa=
s right for some company to be the company that built a new reactor.=C2=A0
He thought that company should be SpaceX, and tried to set up a nuclear tea=
m within the friendly confines of the space giant. Meanwhile, since the DoD=
 had requested proposals, he went on sabbatical to temporarily go full-time=
 on the project, pulling together an informal crack team that included Firm=
ware Engineer Bob Urberger [ https://substack.com/redirect/b260b376-7efa-48=
c9-bcde-ce53e12960df?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa=
8-6m8ExkRNpU ], to submit one. The team came up with a name =E2=80=93 Radia=
nt =E2=80=93 and a logo, and even set up a legal entity through which they =
submitted the proposal.
The team didn=E2=80=99t win the proposal, nor did Doug win his attempt to s=
et up a nuclear team within SpaceX. It was just too hard for a big company =
that had so many other complex things going on.=C2=A0
That was fine. The proposal had confirmed to him that he couldn=E2=80=99t w=
ork on anything but solving this problem, so in 2019, Doug left SpaceX to f=
ound Radiant [ https://substack.com/redirect/49743053-80d0-4dba-b31e-521cd1=
5486d4?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=
=2E
Simulating Radiant
Now that hard tech is undergoing a SpaceX-driven renaissance, there=E2=80=
=99s a belief that a founder can simply leave SpaceX, raise his or her hand=
, and receive millions of venture dollars to build the SpaceX for X.=C2=A0
That was not Doug=E2=80=99s experience founding Radiant.=C2=A0
When he hung up his shingle, Doug=E2=80=99s sum total of experience with nu=
clear power was that one project. He understood the rough shape of what he =
would need to build =E2=80=93 something close to Project Pele=E2=80=99s req=
uirements =E2=80=93 but he didn=E2=80=99t know what the reactor design woul=
d be, how to design a reactor, or anyone who knew how to design a reactor.=
=C2=A0
He set out to remedy those issues in reverse order.=C2=A0
First, he started reaching out to people in the nuclear industry on LinkedI=
n, and was met with a surprisingly positive reception. This is something I=
=E2=80=99ve heard from a number of nuclear founders =E2=80=93 industry vete=
rans are extremely welcoming to fresh talent. One of the suggestions he hea=
rd over and over again in those conversations was to go to the annual Ameri=
can Nuclear Society event to meet more people, so Doug, Bob, and a few othe=
rs went at the end of 2019. They met more people, including Jess Gehin [ ht=
tps://substack.com/redirect/de083649-b8ef-43e0-8c1a-aaa5b06c0a4e?j=3DeyJ1Ij=
oiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], the Associate L=
aboratory Director, Nuclear Science & Technology, at Idaho National Lab (IN=
L).=C2=A0
In early 2020, on Gehin=E2=80=99s invitation, Doug visited INL, where he wa=
lked on top of reactors talking about different technology types. =E2=80=9C=
I fiendishly learned everything I could about fuel, densities, costs,=E2=80=
=9D he said, all information that he would bring into figuring out how to d=
esign a reactor.=C2=A0
Second, he set out to learn reactor design through simulations. He=E2=80=99=
d figured out how to do the necessary modeling work for the proposal he sub=
mitted while at SpaceX (via Radiant Industries), but by his own admission, =
what they submitted was =E2=80=9Creally a Frankenstein, not a good design f=
rom an expert.=E2=80=9D So he turned himself into an expert.=C2=A0
Then, early in Radiant=E2=80=99s life, before the company had raised any mo=
ney, COVID hit. Like many of us, Doug spent much of his lockdown glued to h=
is computer. Unlike many of us, Doug was using his computer to model nuclea=
r reactors.
Taking what he=E2=80=99d learned from conversations, questions, and papers,=
 Doug started running simulations in code, first using a program called Ser=
pent [ https://substack.com/redirect/26954262-ce37-45d7-a781-9c020298fd2f?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], =E2=80=
=9Ca multi-purpose three-dimensional continuous-energy neutron and photon t=
ransport code, developed at VTT Technical Research Centre of Finland since =
2004,=E2=80=9D and then a more modern one called OpenMC [ https://substack.=
com/redirect/20d5aaf2-14a9-45fd-b352-17cd7589425e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb=
8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].=C2=A0
This is what some OpenMC code looks like for a Very High Temperature Reacto=
r (VHTR) [ https://substack.com/redirect/09956559-76f4-423f-a545-307924fdb4=
da?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]:=C2=
=A0=C2=A0
In OpenMC, you can adjust a number of different parameters, like fuel enric=
hment or coolant channel sizes, and the Monte Carlo code simulates a number=
 of particles by making neutrons, picking a random direction for them to he=
ad, and rolling the dice on their starting energies. It outputs metrics tha=
t tell you how the simulated reactor performs, like k-effective.=C2=A0
K-effective is the ratio of the number of neutrons in one generation to the=
 number of neutrons in the previous generation in a nuclear fission chain r=
eaction. As Doug explained, =E2=80=9CIf you get 2.4 neutrons from every fis=
sion reaction, and lose 1.4 neutrons, and 1 gets back to fission, that=E2=
=80=99s critical.=E2=80=9D Meaning, each reaction produces a certain number=
 of neutrons. Some are lost to any number of factors, like absorption in no=
n-fissile materials, leakage from the reactor core, parasitic capture in U-=
238 (you want it to hit the U-235 isotope, not U-238), or absorption in con=
trol rods). If just one neutron survives to set off fission in the next U-2=
35 atom, and so on, then the reaction can sustain and produce power.=C2=A0
There are dozens of parameters and dozens of output metrics in OpenMC, and =
in an actual nuclear reactor. Change one parameter, and all of the outputs =
change. It=E2=80=99s a multivariate problem with no right answer; it depend=
s what you=E2=80=99re solving for. In Doug=E2=80=99s case, he was solving f=
or a reactor that roughly hit Project Pele=E2=80=99s request, but even with=
in that limited design space, there are practically limitless permutations.=
=C2=A0
Luckily, Doug had a lot of time. He ran hundreds and hundreds of simulation=
s, first to get a feel for how different decisions influenced the output, t=
he way you or I might play with a model=E2=80=99s sensitivity to different =
inputs in Excel in order to understand a business. He=E2=80=99d share each =
new batch of runs with his new friends at INL and a particularly helpful pr=
ofessor at UC Berkeley. That professor, he said, enjoyed seeing the frenzie=
d attempts of a novice but SpaceX-credentialed outsider.=C2=A0
Once Doug got far enough down the rabbit hole on a certain design, tracking=
 metrics and responsiveness to tweaks the whole time, he=E2=80=99d throw it=
 all away and start fresh.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CI didn=E2=80=99t know what the hell I was doing,=E2=80=9D he smile=
d, but with each fresh model, he knew a little bit more.
Third and finally, Doug got to a reactor design he liked: a 1 MW High-Tempe=
rature Gas-Cooled Reactor that uses a hydride moderator inside of a graphit=
e core to lower fuel requirements.=C2=A0
Typically, fuel costs aren=E2=80=99t a huge consideration in nuclear reacto=
rs. For a 1 GW reactor, like the Westinghouse AP 1000, nuclear fuel makes u=
