ation.=C2=A0
Back in the first Atomic Age, after the US dropped nuclear bombs on Japan, =
there was tremendous excitement around using that same newfound capability =
that humans had gained, the ability to release huge amounts of energy by sp=
litting atoms, for good.=C2=A0
In 1953, President Eisenhower addressed the United Nations General Assembly=
 to deliver what would come to be known as the =E2=80=9CAtoms for Peace=E2=
=80=9D speech.=C2=A0
President Eisenhower imagined that, =E2=80=9Cif the entire body of the worl=
d's scientists and engineers had adequate amounts of fissionable material w=
ith which to test and develop their ideas, this capability would rapidly be=
 transformed into universal, efficient, and economic usage.=E2=80=9D
They did, and it was. On Age of Miracles [ https://substack.com/redirect/d5=
b34299-d66c-4361-a8ee-2b9b61b70d8b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaM=
ZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], nuclear engineer and author of the excellent =
whatisnuclear.com [ https://substack.com/redirect/5153d753-3962-4912-8f32-b=
0c4f8161a27?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkR=
NpU ] Nick Touran [ https://substack.com/redirect/7b9a5137-eec6-458a-bb90-b=
e14cfba7659?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkR=
NpU ] told me and Julia DeWahl [ https://substack.com/redirect/2090649d-5c8=
7-4133-bb58-0a23c117528b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKb=
qOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] that the period was a time of incredible experimentation=
 in nuclear power:=C2=A0
There was a time back in the 40s, 50s, 60s, where there were a hundred thou=
sand people around the world, the smartest people in the world, all focused=
 on nuclear reactor technology. It was like The Thing. And so there's so mu=
ch interesting information and history and things that people did back then=
=2E It just blows my mind. Every time I=
 go, look, I find something new. We ha=
d lots of small reactors, dozens of small reactors, some of which pretty mu=
ch check all the boxes of the things that we're excited about now. We actua=
lly built them.
People were experimenting with all sorts of nuclear reactor designs, using =
various moderators, coolants, vessels, and sizes. There were Light Water Re=
actors, both Pressurized and Boiling, Heavy Water Reactors, Gas-Cooled Reac=
tors, Liquid Metal Fast Breeder Reactors, Molten Salt Reactors, Organic-coo=
led Reactors, Homogeneous Reactors, and Graphite-Moderated Reactors, among =
others. As Nick pointed out, a lot of the reactor designs startups are exci=
ted about today were first tested way back in the =E2=80=9850s and =E2=80=
=9860s (many such cases in hard tech).=C2=A0
If the phrases =E2=80=9Cnuclear reactor=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cexperimentati=
on=E2=80=9D sound odd together, well, it was a different time. Back then, n=
uclear reactors were governed by the Atomic Energy Commission (AEC), which =
was tasked with both regulating and promoting/developing nuclear technology=
=2E The AEC of course cared about sa=
fety, but it didn=E2=80=99t care only abo=
ut safety. It believed that nuclear power was a force for good and regulate=
d it as such.=C2=A0
Then a couple of things happened, one market-driven and one-government driv=
en.=C2=A0
On the market side, the US Navy, under Admiral Hyman G. Rickover, decided t=
o use Pressurized Water Reactors (PWRs), built by Westinghouse, to power nu=
clear submarines. Westinghouse used this experience to create commercial PW=
R designs, and as more utilities embraced nuclear, and engineers realized t=
he economies of scale present in larger reactors, the US nuclear industry e=
ssentially just made bigger and bigger PWRs.=C2=A0
If you=E2=80=99re picturing a nuclear plant in your head right now, with th=
e hourglass-ish cooling tower, you=E2=80=99re probably picturing a PWR. Six=
ty-three of the ninety-four active nuclear reactors in the US today are PWR=
s, and the other thirty-one are the similar Boiling Water Reactors (BWRs).=
=C2=A0
This explains why the US coalesced around Light Water Reactors back then, b=
ut none of it explains why the DOME is so important to Radiant today. That=
=E2=80=99s the government-driven piece.=C2=A0
In 1974, Congress passed the Energy Reorganization Act of 1974 [ https://su=
bstack.com/redirect/759f0f9e-4f32-42c9-a434-422d358a8c6f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3=
QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], which split the AEC=E2=
=80=99s responsibilities into two organizations:=C2=A0
The Energy Research and Development Administration (ERDA) took over the res=
earch and development aspects of nuclear energy, as well as other energy-re=
lated programs. This became part of the newly-formed Department of Energy (=
DOE) in 1977.
The Nuclear Regulatory Commission (NRC) was given the responsibility for th=
e regulation of civilian nuclear power and nuclear materials.
At the same time, the DoD=E2=80=99s nuclear programs =E2=80=93 including th=
e Naval Nuclear Propulsion Program =E2=80=93 were separated from the civili=
an agencies, meaning that money spent on the defense side wouldn=E2=80=99t =
fund the peaceful use of nuclear energy, practically the polar opposite of =
Eisenhower=E2=80=99s vision of Atoms for Peace.=C2=A0
That decision, although it may not have been the intention at the time, set=
 the nuclear industry in amber as it existed in 1974. In the 50 years since=
 the NRC took over, it has never certified an advanced nuclear reactor (non=
-water cooled) design. The NRC has also not licensed the construction of an=
y new reactor design, including LWRs. Despite the fact that we need clean e=
nergy. Despite the fact that many of the new designs are safer than water-c=
ooled designs!=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s an embarrassment, full stop.=C2=A0
Peeking inside of the embarrassment, part of the problem is the NRC=E2=80=
=99s chicken-and-egg approach to regulation that I mentioned earlier: the N=
RC wants to see data proving that a particular reactor design is safe, but =
it won=E2=80=99t allow companies to test their reactors in order to generat=
e that data! That=E2=80=99s so maddening to even type that it=E2=80=99s a s=
mall miracle any entrepreneur is willing to build a nuclear startup.=C2=A0
But entrepreneurs are clever and resilient, and many are taking novel appro=
aches to getting around the NRC=E2=80=99s roadblocks. And one path around t=
he roadblocks is to test a reactor in one of the DOE=E2=80=99s national lab=
s, like, for example, Idaho National Lab.=C2=A0=C2=A0
Contra the NRC, the DOE is awesome. It=E2=80=99s quite literally the good h=
alf of the AEC. I talked about some of the great work it does on things lik=
e fusion and nuclear safety in my deep dive on Fuse Energy [ https://substa=
ck.com/redirect/c8e5b1a3-6fc3-4605-8910-fc68ea1e1793?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ=
=2Egb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8=
ExkRNpU ], and it also provides loans=20=
and grants to fund the development of new energy technologies, and provides=
 facilities to test advanced reactor designs. Like the DOME.=C2=A0
The =E2=80=9CDOME=E2=80=9D at INL, officially known as the Contained Test F=
acility, was built to house the Experimental Breeder Reactor II [ https://s=
ubstack.com/redirect/994240ee-cd3d-49b1-a52f-e490e569a411?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ=
3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] (EBR-II), a breeder rea=
ctor power plant built and operated by Argonne National Laboratory back in =
the AEC-overseen good ol=E2=80=99 days 1964.=C2=A0
EBR-II was shut down in 1994, and the decades-long decommissioning process =
began. In the 2010s, there were plans to take down the large concrete dome =
from which the facility takes its nickname. Contractors actually cut a gian=
t vertical slit in the dome (lowercase, the actual structure) to begin the =
process. The DOME was on its way out until, miraculously, passionate leader=
