iOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], consumers around=
 the world spent $10 trillion on energy in 2022 before accounting for gover=
nment subsidies, and the vast majority of the world=E2=80=99s population do=
esn=E2=80=99t consume as much energy as they could or should. India=E2=80=
=99s 1.4 billion people, for example, consume 10% the kilowatt-hours of the=
ir American counterparts.=C2=A0
Even Americans don=E2=80=99t consume as much energy as we can or should. Th=
ere is no more direct input to GDP per capita than energy consumption per c=
apita. As the meme goes, there is =E2=80=9CNo such thing as a low-energy ri=
ch country.=E2=80=9D
America today will not look rich by this standard to our grandchildren. Our=
 growth in energy consumption fell off a cliff, or more specifically off th=
e Henry Adams Curve, in the 1970s.=C2=A0
In Where is My Flying Car?, J. Storrs Hall argues that this is why, while m=
any of the sci-fi predictions in the digital world did come true, none of t=
hose predictions in the physical world that required more than 10 kW of ele=
ctricity did.=C2=A0
I won=E2=80=99t belabor this point. I=E2=80=99ve made it before and I wrote=
 about it in more detail in Working Harder and Smarter [ https://substack.c=
om/redirect/df6ee9c5-bf4c-4660-b0c9-6aa3df8b9b63?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8=
J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] if you want the full thing, but =
the point is that if entrepreneurs come up with ways to produce cheap, clea=
n, energy and get it to where it=E2=80=99s needed, people will find a use f=
or it. There is a theory related to this, Jevons Paradox [ https://substack=
=2Ecom/redirect/603e618e-e231-4a75-bc2=
4-8ef5cf655c16?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.g=
b8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], which says that when technolo=
gy increases the efficiency with which a resource is used, people actually =
use more of it, not less, because the lower price induces more demand. Jevo=
ns came up with the theory by observing that the increased efficiency of co=
al use led to more demand for coal. We give people more energy, or more eff=
icient energy, and they find ways to use it.=C2=A0
So that=E2=80=99s reason number one: energy is as close to a bottomless mar=
ket as there is.=C2=A0
The second is that nuclear startups are producing very different products f=
or very different markets. Nuclear reactors are a technology that enables t=
hese companies to serve various needs.=C2=A0
