U ] jokingly refers to them as =E2=80=9CLarge Modular Reactors.=E2=80=9D It=
=E2=80=99s built in pieces in a factory then shipped on site, where it=E2=
=80=99s assembled. But that =E2=80=9Cassembly=E2=80=9D is really a big cons=
truction project, with tons and tons of concrete and rebar and environmenta=
l reviews and weather delays and large crews and all of the rest of the stu=
ff you expect from a large construction project, amplified for all the hoop=
s the NRC makes you jump through and all of the =E2=80=9Cnuclear-grade=E2=
=80=9D parts that cost 100x for basically the same product.=C2=A0
So instead of cost declines, as you=E2=80=99d typically expect to see as yo=
u build more of something, nuclear is actually getting  [ https://substack.=
com/redirect/b8fb3461-4260-4064-953d-1861ff5cbc62?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb=
8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]more  [ https://substack.com/red=
irect/b8fb3461-4260-4064-953d-1861ff5cbc62?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7Gn=
A_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]expensive to build [ https://substack.c=
om/redirect/b8fb3461-4260-4064-953d-1861ff5cbc62?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8=
J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].=C2=A0
Fans of renewables see a chart like this as proof positive that nuclear jus=
t isn=E2=80=99t the future. Solar and batteries are getting much cheaper, n=
uclear isn=E2=80=99t, game over, sorry.=C2=A0
But nuclear has tremendous advantages over renewables in certain areas that=
 matter, like Energy Return on Energy Invested, or EROEI. Like LCOE, EROEI =
isn=E2=80=99t perfect and has its detractors, but it=E2=80=99s a very simpl=
e way to compare various energy sources. This 2022 note from Goehring & Roz=
encwajg, The Distortions of Cheap Energy [ https://substack.com/redirect/4b=
1afc21-8e65-4e99-8ff8-490c20e1407a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaM=
ZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], explains it well:
EROEI measures how much energy is required to generate a useable unit of po=
wer. For example, for every unit of energy =E2=80=9Cinvested=E2=80=9D in th=
e natural gas eco-system (to drill the well, process and transport the gas,=
 build a CCGT power plant, and generate electricity), 30 units of usable po=
wer are released in the form of electricity. Natural gas power generation i=
s said to have one of the best EROEIs at 30:1.
For most of human history, the authors write, EROEI from food and animal fe=
ed was pretty static at 5:1. Coal was a huge unlock, at 10:1. Oil and natur=
al gas were even better, at 30:1. Wind and solar, they argue, are a step ba=
ckward: both have EROEIs around 3.5:1 (after adjusting for intermittency an=
d redundancy).=C2=A0
All hope is not lost, they say. We can still produce clean energy and grow.=
 The authors conclude:=C2=A0
To maintain our standard of surplus and allow for growth, we must adopt an =
energy system with a superior EROEI. Nuclear energy enjoys an EROEI of 100:=
1, three times better than hydrocarbons and 30 times better than renewables=
=2E Moreover, it has extremely low carb=
on intensity. A widespread move toward=
s nuclear power could be as valuable to humanity as moving from biomass to =
coal was in the sixteenth century.
There=E2=80=99s this ongoing debate over whether we need nuclear at all in =
a world in which solar is getting so cheap. One answer, the one that Radian=
t started with, is that nuclear is necessary for space. Another, which the =
Radiant team has learned, is that nuclear is also necessary if we want trul=
y abundant clean energy on earth, too.=C2=A0
While Goehring & Rozencwajg=E2=80=99s nuclear EROEI is higher than most est=
imates I=E2=80=99ve seen, and their solar EROEI is lower, it=E2=80=99s clea=
r that the challenge for nuclear isn=E2=80=99t one of physics. It=E2=80=99s=
 one of our ability to build.=C2=A0
This is the same point made by guests on Age of Miracles, like Valar Atomic=
=E2=80=99s Isaiah Taylor, who compared how much more expensive it is to bui=
ld nuclear reactors than similarly-sized machines of similar complexity bec=
ause of the hurdles we put in our way, and Oklo=E2=80=99s Jake DeWitte, who=
 told us that nuclear has the best =E2=80=9Ccost physics.=E2=80=9D EROEI is=
 one way of quantifying those.=C2=A0
Energy is at the base of everything else, including money. If a particular =
energy source has a higher EROEI than another, it should, in its platonic s=
tate, be a cheaper source of energy, or put another way, the source that ge=
nerates the most wealth per dollar invested.
So the challenge becomes: how do you get nuclear closer to its platonic ide=
al? or, how do you turn nuclear reactors from a construction project to a m=
anufacturing process to bring them down the cost curve?
This is what Fred and Doug realized Radiant might be able to do during that=
