wZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rg=
b(54, 55, 55); text-decoration: underline;">Elon Musk</a></em><span>, &#822=
0;Every week, amid all the technical meetings on engine and rocket design, =
he held one otherworldly meeting called &#8216;Mars Colonizer.&#8217; There=
 he imagined what a Mars colony would look like and how it should be govern=
ed.&#8221;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; l=
ine-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Elon&#8217;s former Chief of Staff, =
Sam Teller, recalled a 2014 SpaceX board meeting on the same theme: &#8220;=
They&#8217;re sitting around seriously discussing plans to build a city on =
Mars and what people will wear there,&#8221; Teller later marveled, &#8220;=
and everyone&#8217;s just acting like this is a totally normal conversation=
=2E&#8221;&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: r=
gb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line=
-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">On the surface, it seems absurd. In 201=
4, the Starship rocket that might one day carry humans to the Red Planet wa=
s nine years away from its first testflight. Starlink, which would fund the=
 journey to Mars, was still five years away. And the first successful landi=
ng of a Falcon 9 first stage, the reusability that would make the whole thi=
ng possible in the first place, wouldn&#8217;t happen for another year and =
a half. But here was the board, spending precious meeting time debating Mar=
tian fashion.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px;=
 line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Your first reaction might be that =
Elon is weird, and he is the boss, and so everyone humors him. His former a=
ssistant, Elissa Butterfield, told Isaacson, &#8220;We tried to avoid ever =
skipping Mars Colonizer, because that was the most fun meeting for him and =
put him in a good mood.&#8221;&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55);=
 font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">But it wasn&#8217=
;t just Elon.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px;=
 line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><a href=3D"https://substack.com/re=
direct/49a7c036-ce29-49e5-8ca0-4a4339cd483d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7G=
nA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); t=
ext-decoration: underline;">Doug Bernauer</a><span>, an eleven-year SpaceX =
veteran, gave up a salary, stock options, and the enviable position as a se=
nior jack-of-all-trades engineer at the world&#8217;s most ambitious compan=
y to fix an existential problem he helped uncover, simulated, solved for, a=
nd presented to Elon and the team in a Mars Colonizer meeting.</span></p><d=
iv class=3D"captioned-image-container-static" style=3D"font-size: 16px; lin=
e-height: 26px; margin: 32px auto;"><figure style=3D"margin: 0 auto; width:=
