color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20p=
x 0;"><strong>Here was the problem</strong><span>: to colonize Mars, you ne=
ed to send Starship up with supplies, then refuel it and send it back to Ea=
rth, all without humans, because untamed Mars is too risky, and the food to=
 feed them weighs too much.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, =
55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><strong>But h=
ow do you refuel Starship on a planet with no fuel?</strong><span>&#160;</s=
pan></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 2=
6px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">It&#8217;s actually possible. You can vaporize th=
e ice that&#8217;s all over Mars into water, run it through an Electrolyzer=
 to split H2O into Hydrogen and Oxygen, pull CO2 from the atmosphere, then =
react Hydrogen and CO2 using the Sabatier reaction to produce methane. Then=
 compress it, cool it to a liquid, fill the tanks, and keep it cool with cr=
yo coolers. The challenge is: that takes a whole lot of power.&#160;</p><p =
style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin=
: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Turns out, you would need over </span><strong>three fo=
otball fields worth of solar panels</strong><span> to produce all of that p=
ower. Assuming that you could get the panels spread out on Mars&#8217; surf=
ace, a task for which the team looked at a number of unorthodox solutions, =
you&#8217;d also need to send up vehicles that could anchor them into Mars&=
#8217; rocky surface. All told, the mass of the panels plus all of the othe=
r machines involved in the process would require two missions.&#160;</span>=
</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px;=
 margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Solar was a no-go. But </span><em>not</em><span=
> powering Mars was not an option, either. What to do?&#160;</span></p><p s=
tyle=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin:=
 0 0 20px 0;"><span>In a meeting with </span><a href=3D"https://substack.co=
m/redirect/15fe7137-e22a-42e8-a9c9-883464b6925d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J=
5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55=
); text-decoration: underline;">Tom Mueller</a><span>, now the CEO of Impul=
se Space, and Elon, Doug remembers, </span><strong>&#8220;Elon said the wor=
d nuclear first.&#8221;</strong><span>&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: r=
gb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Sp=
aceX had no nuclear division. Unlike solar, Elon didn&#8217;t have a nuclea=
r company on the side. The company had no nuclear code, nothing on the topi=
c except for a few studies that Mueller, already a big nuclear fan, had don=
e.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-heigh=
t: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Doug didn&#8217;t know anything about nuclear=
, either, but he knew how to figure things out. In his time at SpaceX, he&#=
8217;d already worked on everything from mining locomotives to space lasers=
=2E So he raised his hand to study the=20=
problem, and in doing so, changed the=20=
trajectory of his career.&#160;</p><h3 class=3D"header-anchor-post" style=
=3D"-moz-appearance: optimizelegibility; -moz-osx-font-smoothing: antialias=
ed; -webkit-appearance: optimizelegibility; -webkit-font-smoothing: antiali=
ased; appearance: optimizelegibility; color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-family: =
'SF Pro Display', -apple-system-headline, system-ui, -apple-system, BlinkMa=
cSystemFont, 'Segoe UI', Roboto, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif, 'Apple Color=
 Emoji', 'Segoe UI Emoji', 'Segoe UI Symbol'; font-size: 1.375em; font-weig=
ht: bold; line-height: 1.16em; margin: 1em 0 0.625em 0; position: relative;=
"><strong>Nuclear on Mars</strong><span>&#160;</span></h3><p style=3D"color=
: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"=
>At first blush, the idea of building nuclear reactors on Mars seems like a=
 fantasy, and a potentially wasteful one at that. The age-old knock against=
 the space program is that we shouldn&#8217;t be spending tens of billions =
of dollars sending rockets to faraway planets when we have so many issues l=
eft to solve right here on our own.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55,=
 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">The counters=
 to that line of thinking are manifold, ranging from the aspirational to th=
e practical.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; =
line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">On the aspirational side, humans ne=
ed a frontier, a just-out-of-reach goal to strive towards. Plus, making hum=
anity multiplanetary is an insurance policy on the most valuable thing in t=
he universe.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; =
line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">More practically, the things we dev=
elop for space directly improve life on earth.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: =
rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><=
span>GPS is the most obvious example. Without satellites, your Google Maps =
wouldn&#8217;t work. But </span><strong>the list of products you use in you=
r daily life that were born out of or improved by space research is shockin=
gly long</strong><span>: cell phone cameras, memory foam, scratch-resistant=
 lenses, cordless tools, water filtration systems, infrared ear thermometer=
s, joysticks, LASIK, artificial limbs, cochlear implants, insulin pumps, so=
ft contact lenses, and baby formula, to name a few. When I finished the Lon=
don Marathon in April, I was quickly wrapped in a reflective blanket of the=
 sort first developed by NASA in 1964.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: r=
gb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><s=
pan>And as Brian Potter highlights in his </span><a href=3D"https://substac=
k.com/redirect/7928f04a-7291-411d-af01-ba4ef2b559cd?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.=
gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55=
, 55); text-decoration: underline;">series on solar</a><span>, at a time wh=
en solar PV electricity was 5x more expensive than batteries and 10,000 mor=
e expensive than electricity from utilities, satellites &#8220;would be the=
 main customer for solar PV for the next 20 years,&#8221; kicking off the t=
echnology&#8217;s earth-altering descent down the cost curve.&#160;</span><=
/p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; =
margin: 0 0 20px 0;">That such a disproportionate amount of innovation woul=
d come from space research is counterintuitive but logical.&#160;</p><p sty=
le=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0=
 0 20px 0;"><span>In </span><em><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/70=
89c430-4942-4d35-8514-724d89e78979?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaM=
ZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); text-decor=
ation: underline;">Taste for Makers</a><span>, </span></em><span>Paul Graha=
m wrote that difficulty can lead to good design:</span></p><blockquote styl=
e=3D"border-left: 4px solid #0c2427; margin: 20px 0; padding: 0;"><p style=
=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 20px 0; margin-left: 20px;"><em><span>When you have to climb a mountain yo=
u toss everything unnecessary out of your pack.&#160; And so an architect w=
ho has to build on a difficult site, or a small budget, will find that </sp=
an><strong>he is forced to produce an elegant design</strong><span>.</span>=
</em></p></blockquote><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; =
line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Space is harder than a mountain: it=
 is extreme, remote, resource-constrained, and unforgiving. Governments, an=
d private companies, are willing to pay large sums of money for solutions, =
often with indefinite payback periods, in a sort of Pascal&#8217;s Wager: t=
hat the ultimate gains will be near-infinitely large.&#160;</p><p style=3D"=
color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20p=
x 0;">Researching for space gives geniuses permission to treat seemingly fa=
ntastical ideas with life-or-death seriousness, with extreme constraints th=
at strip away any considerations except the hard facts, which is exactly wh=
at Doug did when he began studying nuclear on Mars.&#160;</p><p style=3D"co=
lor: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px =
0;">The first question he asked was: could nuclear achieve SpaceX&#8217;s o=
bjectives on Mars?&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: =
16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">He started reading papers and=
 playing around in Python, comparing solar versus nuclear. Pretty soon, he =
realized that nuclear had a number of advantages.&#160;</p><p style=3D"colo=
r: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;=
">For one thing, you could fit everything &#8211; the nuclear reactor, the =
Sabatier reactor, and all supporting machines, in one Starship.&#160;</p><p=
 style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margi=
n: 0 0 20px 0;">Instead of needing to land at the equator, where the sun is=
, the Starship could land at Mars&#8217; North Pole, where the ice is.&#160=
;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px=
; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>If you landed right on the ice, you could inte=
grate a reactor right into the rocket, use the heat it produces to melt a h=
ole, let it freeze back up over the hoses, and end up with a giant well. Th=
is is very similar to a process that humans have undertaken in the Arctic a=
nd Antarctic for decades &#8211; a Rodriguez Well, or Rodwell. The first Ro=
dwell, built at Camp Century in Greenland, just 800 miles from the North Po=
le, in 1958, actually drew its power from a nuclear reactor. In October 202=
0, four years after Doug had the idea, </span><a href=3D"https://substack.c=
om/redirect/09b181e8-fd9e-4464-b40d-fea38da4d9a1?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8=
J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 5=
5); text-decoration: underline;">NASA actually studied the potential of usi=
ng Rodwells on Mars</a><span>, and concluded that it could potentially work=
, although more studies are needed.&#160;</span></p><div class=3D"captioned=
-image-container-static" style=3D"font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margi=
