but it didn&#8217;t care </span><em>only </em><span>about safety. It believ=
ed that nuclear power was a force for good and regulated it as such.&#160;<=
/span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height:=
 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Then a couple of things happened, one market-dr=
iven and one-government driven.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55)=
; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">On the market si=
de, the US Navy, under Admiral Hyman G. Rickover, decided to use Pressurize=
d Water Reactors (PWRs), built by Westinghouse, to power nuclear submarines=
=2E Westinghouse used this experience t=
o create commercial PWR designs, and a=
s more utilities embraced nuclear, and engineers realized the economies of =
scale present in larger reactors, the US nuclear industry essentially just =
made bigger and bigger PWRs.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); f=
ont-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">If you&#8217;re pic=
turing a nuclear plant in your head right now, with the hourglass-ish cooli=
ng tower, you&#8217;re probably picturing a PWR. Sixty-three of the ninety-=
four active nuclear reactors in the US today are PWRs, and the other thirty=
-one are the similar Boiling Water Reactors (BWRs).&#160;</p><div class=3D"=
