>Helium is continuously cycled through the reactor in a closed loop.&#160;<=
/p></li><li style=3D"margin: 8px 0 0 32px; mso-special-format: bullet;"><p =
style=3D"box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; l=
ine-height: 26px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0; padding-left: 4px;">Cool hel=
ium enters the reactor core at lower temperatures and picks up heat from th=
e graphite (the reactions themselves produce energy as heat).&#160;</p></li=
><li style=3D"margin: 8px 0 0 32px; mso-special-format: bullet;"><p style=
=3D"box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-h=
eight: 26px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0; padding-left: 4px;">The helium he=
ats up to about 700&#176;C as it leaves the core and flows to a heat exchan=
ger.</p></li><li style=3D"margin: 8px 0 0 32px; mso-special-format: bullet;=
"><p style=3D"box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16=
px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0; padding-left: 4px;">In =
the heat exchanger, the hot helium heats up supercritical CO2 (sCO2).</p></=
li><li style=3D"margin: 8px 0 0 32px; mso-special-format: bullet;"><p style=
=3D"box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-h=
eight: 26px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0; padding-left: 4px;"><span>The hot=
 sCO2 drives a turbine alternator compressor to generate electricity using =
a closed </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/e053fe71-d0db-4b5a=
-840e-e195dd78114c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-=
6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); text-decoration: underline=
;">Brayton cycle</a><span>.</span></p></li><li style=3D"margin: 8px 0 0 32p=
x; mso-special-format: bullet;"><p style=3D"box-sizing: border-box; color: =
rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0; margin-bott=
om: 0; padding-left: 4px;">The sCO2 is further cooled in the heat sinks and=
 sent back to the heat exchanger.</p></li><li style=3D"margin: 8px 0 0 32px=
; mso-special-format: bullet;"><p style=3D"box-sizing: border-box; color: r=
gb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0; margin-botto=
m: 0; padding-left: 4px;">After transferring its heat, the helium is forced=
 by an electrically-driven turbopump to flow back to the reactor to pick up=
 heat and go through the process again.</p></li></ul><p style=3D"color: rgb=
(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">With=
 me? Good.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; li=
ne-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Helium has some unique attribut=
es that make it potentially safer than the water used in light water reacto=
rs, chief among them that </span><strong>helium doesn&#8217;t become radioa=
ctive as it&#8217;s bombarded with neutrons from the nuclear reaction</stro=
ng><span>. Helium-4, the most common isotope and the one Radiant uses, is s=
upremely tight and stable: it&#8217;s just two protons and two neutrons. Th=
at gives it an extremely low neutron capture cross-section, meaning that wh=
en neutrons hit the helium atoms, they&#8217;re much more likely to scatter=
 than to be absorbed.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); f=
ont-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>All of that t=
o say, if, on the off chance, a Kaleidos suffers an incident and releases i=
ts coolant into the atmosphere, it would just harmlessly float away. </span=
><strong>There would be no radioactive fallout</strong><span>.</span></p><p=
 style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margi=
n: 0 0 20px 0;">That&#8217;s important for any reactor, but it&#8217;s part=
icularly important for smaller reactors that will be located in remote loca=
tions across the globe.</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 1=
6px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>The combination of a hel=
ium primary coolant and supercritical CO2 power generation loop keeps Kalei=
dos safe in accident scenarios while also </span><strong>efficiently conver=
ting heat to electricity</strong><span>.</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(5=
4, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>=
Doug told me that Radiant&#8217;s current design currently achieves &#8220;=
</span><strong>30% average thermal to electric conversion</strong><span>.&#=
8221; Large nuclear reactors typically have about 33-37% efficiency, so 30%=
 is very good for a much smaller system. That said, Doug mentioned that the=
y could potentially increase it to 42% with design improvements in later ge=
nerations, and that their approach has a 49% efficiency ceiling at Kaleidos=
&#8217; scale.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-siz=
e: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">As with anything in reacto=
r design, getting there would come with trade-offs, and the Radiant team wi=
ll continue to look at those trade-offs as they evolve.&#160;</p><p style=
=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 20px 0;">So there you have it. Kaleidos is a 1 MW reactor that uses HALEU =
TRISO fuel, graphite and hydride moderators, helium coolant, and a Brayton =
cycle involving sCO2 in order to deliver a compact, mobile, efficient, and =
affordable product to customers that can go five years between refuelings.&=
#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: =
26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>That leaves us with one Pele requirement: =
</span><strong>passive safety systems that can shut down safely on their ow=
n.&#160;</strong></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; l=
ine-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">While each of the decisions we&#8217=
;ve discussed are designed to optimize for economics, they&#8217;re also de=
signed to optimize for safety. TRISO is meltdown-proof. Helium is non-radio=
active. 1 MW is small enough that even without those features, a meltdown w=
ouldn&#8217;t be catastrophic.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55);=
 font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>In addition=
 to all of those physics-based passive safety features, Radiant &#8211; Bob=
, in particular &#8211; has built a &#8220;</span><strong>Digital Twin</str=
ong><span>&#8221; of the reactor, a systems model of the nuclear reactor to=
 model its safety in various scenarios.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: =
rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">W=
hen I went out to visit Radiant&#8217;s El Segundo HQ in February, Bob let =
me play with it. You can do something like, say, click a button to disable =
the heat sink and model out what happens to the reactor. In the coming mont=
hs, as it builds out the full reactor (without the nuclear fuel, for now), =
it will tie real sensor data from the reactor into the Digital Twin to make=
 real predictions.&#160;</p><div class=3D"captioned-image-container-static"=
 style=3D"font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 32px auto;"><figure s=
